data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and more specific asserts that give better failure messages than `Assert.IsTrue`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Count checks — failure shows actual vs expected
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // All items match a condition
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive),
        "Expected all users to be active");

    // Check a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"),
        "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)`** — on failure reports `Expected: 3, Actual: 7` instead of just `Assert.IsTrue failed`
- **`Assert.IsTrue` with a message** — when a bool check is unavoidable, add a message string so failures are diagnosable
- **`users.Any()` over `users.Single()`** — `Single` throws an unhelpful `InvalidOperationException` if the sequence has 0 or 2+ matches; use `Any` for existence checks
- **`users.Count` (property)** over **`users.Count()` (LINQ)** — avoids unnecessary enumeration on `List<T>`

**Other `CollectionAssert` helpers worth knowing:**

```csharp
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual); // same items, any order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);      // same items, same order
```

For richer fluent assertions, consider **FluentAssertions** (`users.Should().OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)`), which produces even more descriptive failure messages.
